<h2 id="how">How to find the centre in your town</h2>
<p>For the few remaining towns with no listed address, it should be relatively 
  straightforward to find out about the planning application or planning permission. 
  Your local authority makes all such information public. Search your local government 
  website for applications by a company called 'Mapeley' or variations on this 
  name (e.g. 'Mapeley Estates Limited' or 'Mapeley ABI Provider'). The site may 
  already be a Revenue Enquiry Centre. You may have to ask at the council offices 
  or town hall if the information is not available online, but planning officers 
  are helpful, neutral in the process, and used to dealing with public enquiries.</p>
<p>If the plans have already been approved, do not despair - you will still have 
  found out at least one crucial piece of information that the UK IPS may not 
  yet have published: the actual street address of the centre. There may also 
  be details of the size of the intended facility and its opening hours, for example. 
  Please let us know what you discover. You can <a href="mailto:passports@no2id.net">send 
  an e-mail</a> or write to our office.</p>
 
<p>Several of our supporters discovered the street location of their local interrogation 
  centre by identifying planning applications for the installation of air conditioning 
  (or 'condensing') units in offices that fit the correct profile, i.e. they are 
  part of a Revenue Enquiry Centre or other HMRC building, and the company involved 
  is Mapeley - usually operating through an agent. For example, in <a href="http://www.iwight.com/council/departments/planning/appsdip/AppDetails3.aspx?frmId=13386">Newport 
  IoW</a> the application was made by a Shirley Carter of Morgan Lovell plc <em>on 
  behalf of</em> Mapeley ABI Provider, Matthew Milroy. Such applications can be 
  double-checked if floorplans are available by looking for 'interview rooms' 
  marked on the plans.</p> 
<br />
<h2 id="what">What you can do</h2>
<p>Now that most of the centres are open, we are very eager to speak with people 
  who have been called in for interview. Few details have yet emerged as to what 
  <em>exactly</em> goes on, though we know that officials will have access to 
  a dossier of up to 200 personal questions from which they will ask a selection. 
  The process by which you are awarded or denied a passport appears completely 
  arbitrary. <strong>If you have been called for interview <a href="mailto:passports@no2id.net">please 
  send us an e-mail</a> or write to our office.</strong></p>
<p>If the centre's application has not yet been approved, planning rules give 
  you a chance to oppose the development and to make other people aware of what 
  is going on. There are many ways to raise objections and appeal decisions. It 
  is a well-known process and lots of people have skills and experience. Local 
  councilors and Civic Societies will know all about it. And there is plenty of 
  information available for beginners. See, for example: <a href="http://www.planninghelp.org.uk/stop-or-improve-bad-development/">http://www.planninghelp.org.uk/stop-or-improve-bad-development/</a></p>
<p>Your formal objection needs to be on valid planning grounds, e.g. lack of available 
  parking, nuisance to neighbours, etc. But it will let you start a debate in 
  local media (on the letters pages of your local papers, on radio, and so forth). 
  And it is a chance to get everyone who cares about planning questions involved. 
  That will help more people understand about ID cards and the database state. 
  The reality of the interrogation centres will make people take notice.</p>
